Dear Nick,

Pleased to connect with you via email.

The focus of my work over the last few weeks has been the prototype index-based crop insurance, using soil moisture rather than met variables (prec, temp). Following the service template (https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1fIlfBsWeN4P_k-mEr6_OCklEY11Zig9T) I've been working on the soil moisture index algorithm. To do this, I'm currently setting up an implementation of AquaCrop-OS to generate a dataset showing crop phenology (maize, to start with) for multiple points across SSA and for many years (1980s->). Treating the unique (place, growing season) crop phenology time series as "truth", I plan to relate crop development to soil moisture and identify thresholds during the growing season that can be used as the basis of the insurance index. As observations of crop development become available we can refine the index: at the moment I'm focusing on getting something up and running. 

Obviously to develop an operational service we will need to produce estimates of soil moisture for specific sites in near real time. As Wouter mentioned, I've started work on a "front-end" to this service using the RShiny tool. At the moment this just visualises soil moisture using a simple water balance model using historical data. The next task will be to replace this with a crop model, and work on methods to assimilate the observational data which will become available. I had planned to use the AquaCrop-OS model for this, but I'm happy to change at this stage if there are strategic reasons for using WOFOST/PCSE.

Please do let me know if you require any further information.

Thanks,
Simon

P.s. in WP3 we discussed the potential for me to visit Kenya at the end of June/start of July, to coincide with your visit. Have you been able to finalise dates for this?  

